WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:10.000
From the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.

00:00:10.000 --> 00:00:14.000
Okay, this is Billy Bud.

00:00:14.000 --> 00:00:18.000
Today is Wednesday, March 13, 2013.

00:00:18.000 --> 00:00:24.000
My name is Dr. John Dittmer and I am here in Tchula, Mississippi with the videographer John Bishop.

00:00:24.000 --> 00:00:30.000
To interview Rosie Head, a leading civil rights activist in the Holmes County Mississippi Movement.

00:00:30.000 --> 00:00:38.000
This interview will become part of the Smithsonian's National Museum of African American History and Culture in Washington, DC.

00:00:38.000 --> 00:00:44.000
Ms. Hatt, we're delighted to have you here today and we thank you for taking the time to talk with us.

00:00:44.000 --> 00:00:49.000
I'd like to begin by asking you about your family.

00:00:49.000 --> 00:00:51.000
Were you born and raised in Holmes County?

00:00:51.000 --> 00:00:55.000
I was born in Holmes County.

00:00:55.000 --> 00:01:01.000
And, tell us what were your parents' parents' duties for living?

00:01:01.000 --> 00:01:07.000
My dad was a carpenter and a sharecropper.

00:01:07.000 --> 00:01:13.000
And we worked in the cat and field, corn fields.

00:01:13.000 --> 00:01:20.000
And the gardener said we called truck patches, raised all our foos.

00:01:20.000 --> 00:01:29.000
And we had cows, horses, news, chickens, and hogs.

00:01:29.000 --> 00:01:32.000
A real farm, then.

00:01:32.000 --> 00:01:35.000
Did you have brothers and sisters?

00:01:35.000 --> 00:01:40.000
I had two brothers and seven sisters.

00:01:40.000 --> 00:01:42.000
And where are you on that chain?

00:01:42.000 --> 00:01:45.000
I'm about the sixth.

00:01:46.000 --> 00:01:51.000
And you have a number of members of your family.

00:01:51.000 --> 00:01:53.000
You want to wait till the train goes on.

00:01:53.000 --> 00:01:56.000
You don't immediately.

00:01:56.000 --> 00:01:59.000
Yeah, I'm just going.

00:01:59.000 --> 00:02:01.000
Okay, but we're back.

00:02:01.000 --> 00:02:04.000
So your family, your father was a carpenter.

00:02:04.000 --> 00:02:07.000
What did he do?

00:02:07.000 --> 00:02:08.000
Build houses?

00:02:08.000 --> 00:02:10.000
Build houses.

00:02:10.000 --> 00:02:13.000
And did he have a crew who was he working with?

00:02:13.000 --> 00:02:16.000
Mostly he worked by himself during that time.

00:02:16.000 --> 00:02:24.000
Later on in life, he started to work with another guy that was friend of his, Mr. Horton.

00:02:24.000 --> 00:02:27.000
We interviewed Mr. Bruce the other day.

00:02:27.000 --> 00:02:32.000
He was talking about the work that he was doing as a carpenter.

00:02:32.000 --> 00:02:37.000
Did your father apprentice himself to anyone?

00:02:37.000 --> 00:02:40.000
Or was he just naturally talented there?

00:02:40.000 --> 00:02:43.000
I was just naturally.

00:02:43.000 --> 00:02:48.000
What was it like to grow up in this town?

00:02:48.000 --> 00:02:53.000
It was, I grew up in Lexington.

00:02:53.000 --> 00:02:56.000
I was six years old when I left Lexington.

00:02:56.000 --> 00:02:58.000
And I moved to Greenwood.

00:02:58.000 --> 00:03:04.000
My father had him to, if I had to farm on a plantation on my own,

00:03:04.000 --> 00:03:07.000
to keep their houses up.

00:03:07.000 --> 00:03:11.000
And I lived in Greenwood about ten years.

00:03:11.000 --> 00:03:13.000
Okay, well tell us about Greenwood.

00:03:13.000 --> 00:03:16.000
What was it, what was it, the big change from Lexington?

00:03:16.000 --> 00:03:18.000
It was, it was.

00:03:18.000 --> 00:03:21.000
But we lived out in the country.

00:03:21.000 --> 00:03:25.000
And every once in a while we'd get to go to town.

00:03:25.000 --> 00:03:33.000
And it was exciting to go and see all the things going on in Greenwood.

00:03:33.000 --> 00:03:40.000
And mostly we worked out on the farm, picking and chopping cotton.

00:03:40.000 --> 00:03:46.000
And we did, we were old enough to go in the fields.

00:03:46.000 --> 00:03:50.000
We were babysitting the younger children.

00:03:50.000 --> 00:03:57.000
And we started, I started working in the fields when I was seven years old.

00:03:57.000 --> 00:04:00.000
You were chopping and picking with your hands up?

00:04:01.000 --> 00:04:07.000
Yes, I'd rather be, I would be the crowd, be sitting in the house, maybe sitting.

00:04:07.000 --> 00:04:11.000
So I proved that I could do it.

00:04:11.000 --> 00:04:14.000
So what was the real family affair of that?

00:04:14.000 --> 00:04:15.000
It was.

00:04:15.000 --> 00:04:18.000
Tell us about going to school.

00:04:18.000 --> 00:04:24.000
I went to the first year, when I was six years old, I didn't get to go to school.

00:04:24.000 --> 00:04:28.000
I was supposed to go to a school called Hickory Springs in Lexington.

00:04:28.000 --> 00:04:32.000
But you had to walk across a creek to get to the school.

00:04:32.000 --> 00:04:34.000
And I was too little to go.

00:04:34.000 --> 00:04:35.000
So I had to stay home.

00:04:35.000 --> 00:04:40.000
And when we moved to Greenwood, just before I turned seven.

00:04:40.000 --> 00:04:43.000
And I started to school in that January.

00:04:43.000 --> 00:04:48.000
And we walked to school about five Mileston.

00:04:48.000 --> 00:04:56.000
And when I was about ten, they started giving us buses.

00:04:56.000 --> 00:05:01.000
So we still had to walk about two, three Mileston to the bus stop.

00:05:01.000 --> 00:05:08.000
Oh, that's quite a sacrifice to make for an education.

00:05:08.000 --> 00:05:11.000
Most of the young kids today wouldn't know what to do.

00:05:11.000 --> 00:05:13.000
What is the situation like that?

00:05:13.000 --> 00:05:16.000
Yeah, we walked.

00:05:16.000 --> 00:05:19.000
We went to a school that was a church.

00:05:19.000 --> 00:05:21.000
And it was just the one room.

00:05:21.000 --> 00:05:26.000
All the grades pre-premise through eighth grade was in that school.

00:05:26.000 --> 00:05:28.000
How many teachers did you have?

00:05:28.000 --> 00:05:29.000
One teacher.

00:05:29.000 --> 00:05:32.000
One teacher for all eighth grades.

00:05:32.000 --> 00:05:37.000
And what were your favorite subjects?

00:05:37.000 --> 00:05:41.000
I always loved reading.

00:05:41.000 --> 00:05:49.000
The church was an important part of the community.

00:05:49.000 --> 00:05:51.000
Was it your family as well?

00:05:51.000 --> 00:05:52.000
It was.

00:05:52.000 --> 00:05:59.000
I remember we said, have to get up and walk to the Sunday school with every Sunday morning.

00:05:59.000 --> 00:06:04.000
And regular service would be one Sunday of my, but Sunday school was every Sunday.

00:06:04.000 --> 00:06:12.000
And if it was like during the summer when it was hot, the dust was like up here on the legs.

00:06:12.000 --> 00:06:14.000
And it was real hot.

00:06:14.000 --> 00:06:20.000
We had to carry our shoes in our hands and carry our wet cloth so that when we get to church,

00:06:20.000 --> 00:06:24.000
we could wash out legs and feed and put our socks on shoes like that.

00:06:24.000 --> 00:06:26.000
Because you're wearing your Sunday best?

00:06:26.000 --> 00:06:28.000
Yes.

00:06:28.000 --> 00:06:31.000
Yeah.

00:06:31.000 --> 00:06:38.000
Well, we're going to be talking about civil rights and the racial situation in Mississippi.

00:06:38.000 --> 00:06:40.000
What was segregation?

00:06:40.000 --> 00:06:44.000
Were you aware of segregation when you were in Greenwood?

00:06:44.000 --> 00:06:45.000
Oh, yes.

00:06:45.000 --> 00:06:46.000
Very much so.

00:06:46.000 --> 00:06:50.000
My mom cooked for the plantation owner.

00:06:50.000 --> 00:06:54.000
And the younger children, there were three of us.

00:06:54.000 --> 00:06:59.000
There was two little, that first to go to the fields.

00:06:59.000 --> 00:07:07.000
And we had to walk across with her to the plantation owner's house.

00:07:07.000 --> 00:07:11.000
And I remember we had this little girl, her name was Corinne,

00:07:11.000 --> 00:07:14.000
And my mom had to call her Miss Corrine.

00:07:14.000 --> 00:07:19.000
I remember she could play out with us, but we couldn't come in the house,

00:07:19.000 --> 00:07:21.000
where she could play outside with her.

00:07:21.000 --> 00:07:24.000
And you had an understanding of what was going on now,

00:07:24.000 --> 00:07:28.000
or did you have to be told that there are certain things you couldn't do?

00:07:28.000 --> 00:07:36.000
Then we knew, because my family was a can that talked at home to all of the children

00:07:36.000 --> 00:07:43.000
to make sure they knew what the rules for our family was and what we couldn't do.

00:07:43.000 --> 00:07:48.000
So we would tell her how to play, so we could do what we couldn't do.

00:07:48.000 --> 00:07:52.000
Was the plantation owner fair in terms of settlement?

00:07:52.000 --> 00:07:54.000
Oh, no, I can remember.

00:07:54.000 --> 00:08:04.000
We would farm that land, and we would pick, we could pick at least a bale kind of day.

00:08:04.000 --> 00:08:08.000
We would pick some time, we would work on Saturday morning,

00:08:08.000 --> 00:08:11.000
and we would pick out six bales of cotton.

00:08:11.000 --> 00:08:18.000
And at the end of the year, like the day before Christmas,

00:08:18.000 --> 00:08:24.000
they would, every farmer would be called in to the office of the plantation owner.

00:08:24.000 --> 00:08:31.000
And we would have picked out whether we were supposed to get half of what we would make on the farm.

00:08:31.000 --> 00:08:35.000
And we would pick some 75 to 80 bales of cotton a year.

00:08:35.000 --> 00:08:39.000
And I can remember every time my dad would come back home,

00:08:39.000 --> 00:08:45.000
they would like you to walk up to the barn or the shop where they paid off,

00:08:45.000 --> 00:08:49.000
what they call you, and say, if you made any money.

00:08:49.000 --> 00:08:53.000
And my dad would always come back and when he would get back home,

00:08:53.000 --> 00:08:57.000
we always waited up for him, and he said, I'm going to take his head off.

00:08:57.000 --> 00:08:59.000
And he always called my mom, baby.

00:08:59.000 --> 00:09:03.000
And he just said, baby, we came out in the hole again.

00:09:03.000 --> 00:09:09.000
And he said that man, you said he could just hear me every time he would go in

00:09:09.000 --> 00:09:16.000
would say, well, Robert, I'm sorry, but you didn't clear nothing, you came out in the hole.

00:09:16.000 --> 00:09:20.000
Did they hurt issue and everything? Was there a company store?

00:09:20.000 --> 00:09:21.000
Did they get a job?

00:09:21.000 --> 00:09:25.000
There was a company store, and they gave us, it was what, 12 of us.

00:09:25.000 --> 00:09:33.000
And they gave us $35 a month to get that much from the store.

00:09:33.000 --> 00:09:43.000
And so it was pretty much the same situation that had been going on for almost a hundred years then.

00:09:43.000 --> 00:09:51.000
Yeah, well, as a kid, what was your reaction when you saw that you had been cheated?

00:09:51.000 --> 00:09:53.000
Your family and then cheated?

00:09:53.000 --> 00:10:00.000
It was a hurting thing, everybody knew that that's the time we looked forward to Christmas

00:10:00.000 --> 00:10:04.000
and we would get something toys or something new.

00:10:04.000 --> 00:10:11.000
But they made sure you get food and stuff like that, you could go to the store and get that.

00:10:11.000 --> 00:10:19.000
And I remember my mom used to make dolls for us, like the sacks that you buy, flour in.

00:10:19.000 --> 00:10:24.000
And she would make our clothes for little flour sacks and meal sacks.

00:10:24.000 --> 00:10:28.000
And she would make dolls for us.

00:10:28.000 --> 00:10:34.000
And we would find our dolls and apple and our orange and some nuts raising.

00:10:34.000 --> 00:10:39.000
And I can remember that so well, they were the best raisins I've ever.

00:10:39.000 --> 00:10:43.000
Every Christmas, and you could smell it all over the house, because when they bring it in,

00:10:43.000 --> 00:10:48.000
they would put it in the closet so nobody would mess with it until the right time.

00:10:48.000 --> 00:10:52.000
And that's what we would look forward to.

00:10:52.000 --> 00:10:56.000
So your folks tried to give you as normal a childhood as a good service?

00:10:56.000 --> 00:10:58.000
They did.

00:10:58.000 --> 00:11:01.000
But there was a lot going on then.

00:11:01.000 --> 00:11:06.000
You had, of course, the lynching a murder of Emmett Till.

00:11:06.000 --> 00:11:07.000
Yes.

00:11:07.000 --> 00:11:10.000
And he was about your age, what?

00:11:10.000 --> 00:11:12.000
I tell us about it.

00:11:13.000 --> 00:11:19.000
You're learning about it and what your conversations in the family and what it is all mean.

00:11:19.000 --> 00:11:22.000
I can remember.

00:11:22.000 --> 00:11:32.000
We lived in this house that was across behind the boss, the plantation on this house across the living.

00:11:32.000 --> 00:11:39.000
And we had a radio, we had TV then, we had a radio.

00:11:39.000 --> 00:11:47.000
And we heard it on the radio where my mom heard she was cooking and she heard it and she called everybody and said,

00:11:47.000 --> 00:11:53.000
and she called it mining right across from where he was at this store.

00:11:53.000 --> 00:11:56.000
I went to school there.

00:11:56.000 --> 00:11:58.000
That's the school I went to.

00:11:58.000 --> 00:12:01.000
We'd walk over across the railroad to that store every day.

00:12:01.000 --> 00:12:04.000
And we had some pennies and nickels.

00:12:04.000 --> 00:12:06.000
We'd walk over there.

00:12:06.000 --> 00:12:09.000
She was in the wild for (Carolyn) Bryant + Roy Bryant.

00:12:09.000 --> 00:12:12.000
Mrs. (Carolyn) Bryant + Roy Bryant, Mrs. (Carolyn) Bryant + Roy Bryant.

00:12:12.000 --> 00:12:15.000
She was waiting for him for (Carolyn) Bryant + Roy Bryant.

00:12:15.000 --> 00:12:17.000
What kind of a person was?

00:12:17.000 --> 00:12:22.000
She was so sad when we went to the store.

00:12:22.000 --> 00:12:25.000
She was thinking, do you going to try to pick up something or something like that?

00:12:25.000 --> 00:12:31.000
She would make sure you stay in one side and wait your turn and come and spend your penny or nickel or whatever.

00:12:31.000 --> 00:12:33.000
She was afraid you'd steal from her.

00:12:33.000 --> 00:12:35.000
Not a nice person.

00:12:35.000 --> 00:12:40.000
Did you know in the town, the town that you were staying with?

00:12:40.000 --> 00:12:42.000
No, I didn't really know that.

00:12:42.000 --> 00:12:47.000
There was a school bus there when we started getting bus.

00:12:47.000 --> 00:12:51.000
I lived near Greenwood about a mile out of Greenwood.

00:12:51.000 --> 00:12:54.000
And mine is about 8 to 10 Mileston.

00:12:54.000 --> 00:12:56.000
We went on school bus up there.

00:12:56.000 --> 00:13:00.000
I didn't know any people that pay my money.

00:13:00.000 --> 00:13:02.000
I talked with a number of civil rights workers.

00:13:02.000 --> 00:13:06.000
And they said, you know, the pill was about their age.

00:13:06.000 --> 00:13:09.000
They realized that it could be them.

00:13:09.000 --> 00:13:12.000
Did the folks give you any special instructions after that?

00:13:12.000 --> 00:13:17.000
There was no, you know, just staying out place and doing what they tell us to do.

00:13:17.000 --> 00:13:23.000
And now, they, all my dad always said that God was going to take care of us.

00:13:23.000 --> 00:13:25.000
And we do the right thing.

00:13:25.000 --> 00:13:28.000
And we just did what he asked us to do.

00:13:28.000 --> 00:13:31.000
And we said it was right for us to do.

00:13:31.000 --> 00:13:34.000
So you stayed out of trouble for a while then.

00:13:34.000 --> 00:13:37.000
Until you started causing something.

00:13:37.000 --> 00:13:38.000
Yes.

00:13:38.000 --> 00:13:43.000
So, after in the late 1950s, you were what, teenager?

00:13:43.000 --> 00:13:46.000
What were you doing then?

00:13:46.000 --> 00:13:51.000
I was still suffering and peaking cat.

00:13:51.000 --> 00:13:58.000
And then my dad finally saved up enough money to buy a new car.

00:13:58.000 --> 00:14:02.000
And he was just a seven, she really brand new.

00:14:02.000 --> 00:14:05.000
And you know how you had to pay something down.

00:14:05.000 --> 00:14:17.000
And the boss had, he had gotten where he wanted the men to come and work.

00:14:17.000 --> 00:14:21.000
But he wouldn't let them come in his office to pick up the paycheck.

00:14:21.000 --> 00:14:26.000
He would ask them to send their wives to pick up the paycheck.

00:14:26.000 --> 00:14:34.000
But my dad, my mom said he tried to talk to the black women.

00:14:34.000 --> 00:14:39.000
He liked black women, the way he wanted to use them.

00:14:39.000 --> 00:14:45.000
But my dad refused to let my mom go and pick his shake up.

00:14:45.000 --> 00:14:47.000
And he would have better get it.

00:14:47.000 --> 00:14:50.000
And he refused to give it to him.

00:14:50.000 --> 00:14:53.000
And told him, he asked him for it.

00:14:53.000 --> 00:14:56.000
He had laid his keys down on the counter.

00:14:56.000 --> 00:15:03.000
The man picked his keys up and he told him he wouldn't get his car, his keys are his check.

00:15:03.000 --> 00:15:07.000
And he told him, it was all right, if that's what you want to do.

00:15:07.000 --> 00:15:15.000
But he won't need to be paying him a check anymore because he wouldn't be there.

00:15:15.000 --> 00:15:20.000
But he thought he had to check the keys and he thought he couldn't leave.

00:15:20.000 --> 00:15:22.000
So, but he had a second pair of keys and all.

00:15:22.000 --> 00:15:24.000
And we left that night.

00:15:24.000 --> 00:15:26.000
We left that plantation and moved to Chua.

00:15:26.000 --> 00:15:28.000
I had an aunt living down in Tchula,

00:15:28.000 --> 00:15:30.000
And we moved there.

00:15:30.000 --> 00:15:35.000
The guy where we could in the car and moved down there in the neighborhood kept the furniture.

00:15:35.000 --> 00:15:38.000
But I understand that he scared her the next morning.

00:15:38.000 --> 00:15:40.000
And she just gave up the furniture to him.

00:15:40.000 --> 00:15:41.000
She had it.

00:15:41.000 --> 00:15:44.000
So we had to start all over again then.

00:15:44.000 --> 00:15:46.000
Did they try to get you back?

00:15:46.000 --> 00:15:48.000
Let's say you owe them money already.

00:15:48.000 --> 00:15:51.000
He tried to get the car away from us.

00:15:51.000 --> 00:15:59.000
But it was, you know, then they had contact with where they could talk to this farmer, this person.

00:15:59.000 --> 00:16:03.000
And they stopped you from getting work there, getting in the account of money.

00:16:03.000 --> 00:16:09.000
So my dad lost a car and that was his way of getting around and making money and doing carbon award.

00:16:09.000 --> 00:16:13.000
And that was, that was how I fought.

00:16:13.000 --> 00:16:17.000
Was it really, like, to be a weight in the plantation and in Chua, Chua?

00:16:17.000 --> 00:16:27.000
Because most of the people, black people around Chua, that project had been given to people then down in Mileston.

00:16:27.000 --> 00:16:31.000
And we were able to get one of those houses.

00:16:31.000 --> 00:16:33.000
And did you farm there?

00:16:33.000 --> 00:16:35.000
We did.

00:16:35.000 --> 00:16:37.000
Certain stances were better?

00:16:37.000 --> 00:16:40.000
My sister's better.

00:16:40.000 --> 00:16:42.000
And well then what happened?

00:16:42.000 --> 00:16:44.000
What were you, you were in Tchula now?

00:16:44.000 --> 00:16:45.000
How old are you?

00:16:45.000 --> 00:16:48.000
Oh, I was 17.

00:16:48.000 --> 00:16:58.000
And I kept, there were lots of people around that you could go and chop and pick cotton and buy the day.

00:16:58.000 --> 00:17:07.000
And I did bed for about six, seven years of pick cotton and chop for a dollar and 50 cents a day.

00:17:07.000 --> 00:17:11.000
And pick cotton and for a dollar a hundred.

00:17:11.000 --> 00:17:17.000
And I could pick about 500 a day and that was just...

00:17:17.000 --> 00:17:21.000
Now did that money go all to the family or did you have some of them?

00:17:21.000 --> 00:17:24.000
That's it had to go to the family.

00:17:24.000 --> 00:17:28.000
So everybody was pitching in?

00:17:28.000 --> 00:17:32.000
So when did you go out on your own?

00:17:32.000 --> 00:17:35.000
For India.

00:17:35.000 --> 00:17:41.000
In 1964, so it's three and 64.

00:17:41.000 --> 00:17:53.000
We started talking together with some people from Greenwood about the movement that different people were coming into Mississippi to help people learn to register the vote.

00:17:53.000 --> 00:18:02.000
So we started going to Greenwood like certain nights they would have meetings, certain days they would have meetings there.

00:18:02.000 --> 00:18:07.000
We started going there until we got a young man to come to Tchula.

00:18:07.000 --> 00:18:09.000
And we started having the meetings out there.

00:18:09.000 --> 00:18:19.000
We had a freedom school and one of the churches in that area let us use the church to have our meetings and everything.

00:18:19.000 --> 00:18:22.000
Let me back up a little bit.

00:18:22.000 --> 00:18:31.000
And because the question I'm always asking is what motivates you to become involved in the civil rights movement?

00:18:31.000 --> 00:18:36.000
Why? Because not very many people did early on.

00:18:36.000 --> 00:18:39.000
Especially you were probably one of the first around here, right?

00:18:39.000 --> 00:18:40.000
Yes.

00:18:40.000 --> 00:18:47.000
You heard about the meetings in Greenwood and then did several of you go?

00:18:47.000 --> 00:18:59.000
Yes, it had. We've been talking about it since I've heard my dad and other people talking since the end of the year about we're going to have to do something.

00:18:59.000 --> 00:19:03.000
It just kept not doing anything.

00:19:03.000 --> 00:19:07.000
And finally it just came to the point where they found something that could help.

00:19:07.000 --> 00:19:10.000
And they would tell us all about it.

00:19:10.000 --> 00:19:20.000
And I just got interested. It was just like it was a way I knew what the people there was in charge.

00:19:20.000 --> 00:19:23.000
I knew what they thought of us and how they were treating us.

00:19:23.000 --> 00:19:25.000
And I just knew that was a better way.

00:19:25.000 --> 00:19:29.000
And just went out there hoping it was clean.

00:19:29.000 --> 00:19:36.000
So what, do you remember, did you first go to a meeting in Greenwood in 62 or what?

00:19:36.000 --> 00:19:39.000
Who were the SNCC people who were?

00:19:39.000 --> 00:19:42.000
John Ball.

00:19:42.000 --> 00:19:47.000
And I can't miss in this fellow name. He was a blocker.

00:19:47.000 --> 00:19:49.000
He was a sound blocker, yes.

00:19:49.000 --> 00:19:57.000
Stokely Carmichael, Bob Moses, and Lawrence Guyot.

00:19:57.000 --> 00:20:03.000
There's a lot of people, different people than I'm not getting their names.

00:20:03.000 --> 00:20:06.000
That sort of (Willie Wazir) Peacock, I think.

00:20:06.000 --> 00:20:08.000
Yes, probably.

00:20:08.000 --> 00:20:11.000
And Hollis Watkins.

00:20:11.000 --> 00:20:13.000
Hollis is still going strong.

00:20:13.000 --> 00:20:18.000
Yes he is. Good name.

00:20:18.000 --> 00:20:22.000
So you went to the meetings and tell me about a typical meeting.

00:20:22.000 --> 00:20:24.000
What went on in the meeting?

00:20:24.000 --> 00:20:31.000
We would just sit around and talk about the things that

00:20:31.000 --> 00:20:36.000
was unfair to black people as like the segregated places, the schools,

00:20:36.000 --> 00:20:41.000
and the different places like the courthouse, and the water fountain,

00:20:41.000 --> 00:20:46.000
and things around the bathroom, restaurants, and things that we couldn't use.

00:20:46.000 --> 00:20:52.000
We talked about how we were second class citizens, but we were having to pay taxes

00:20:52.000 --> 00:20:54.000
like first class citizens.

00:20:54.000 --> 00:20:58.000
And we talked about things that could be available to us.

00:20:58.000 --> 00:21:01.000
And we just had to pay after getting it.

00:21:01.000 --> 00:21:09.000
And we talked about how we had to do to get registered to vote,

00:21:09.000 --> 00:21:11.000
and that's where the power was.

00:21:11.000 --> 00:21:17.000
We could get some of the things that we needed if we were first class citizens

00:21:17.000 --> 00:21:20.000
and that would make us first class citizens.

00:21:20.000 --> 00:21:24.000
Did you work in the voter registration campaign in Greenwood,

00:21:24.000 --> 00:21:27.000
or did you wait till it came here?

00:21:27.000 --> 00:21:30.000
I did you.

00:21:30.000 --> 00:21:32.000
I believe it was John Ball.

00:21:32.000 --> 00:21:33.000
He was a do-it-all.

00:21:33.000 --> 00:21:35.000
He John Ball came to Holmes County.

00:21:35.000 --> 00:21:39.000
And of course, there's the first work team.

00:21:39.000 --> 00:21:42.000
Were you aware of what was going on then?

00:21:42.000 --> 00:21:43.000
Yes.

00:21:43.000 --> 00:21:46.000
The Mileston was very close.

00:21:46.000 --> 00:21:47.000
Oh really?

00:21:47.000 --> 00:21:50.000
The mission is kind of the assistance.

00:21:50.000 --> 00:21:53.000
They were all close people.

00:21:53.000 --> 00:21:55.000
We went to church together.

00:21:55.000 --> 00:21:59.000
Miss Carnegie was real, after real early.

00:21:59.000 --> 00:22:01.000
She was real.

00:22:01.000 --> 00:22:03.000
Yeah, what's she talking about?

00:22:03.000 --> 00:22:05.000
She was real warrior.

00:22:05.000 --> 00:22:07.000
Something else, yes you were.

00:22:10.000 --> 00:22:16.000
So what about the other people who were Carpenterinbo was the name that comes up.

00:22:16.000 --> 00:22:18.000
Tell me about Terinbo.

00:22:18.000 --> 00:22:20.000
That's the Terinbo.

00:22:20.000 --> 00:22:23.000
There's just one type of Terinbo.

00:22:23.000 --> 00:22:25.000
He was fearless.

00:22:25.000 --> 00:22:28.000
He would get up in the media.

00:22:28.000 --> 00:22:31.000
And when he started talking to everybody, we'll catch on.

00:22:31.000 --> 00:22:38.000
He would just talk and tell all the things that the people had been doing to black people.

00:22:38.000 --> 00:22:44.000
And he would tell them, actually they want to have that going on all the ways that you want to do something about it.

00:22:44.000 --> 00:22:47.000
And he would get people all stereotyphing.

00:22:47.000 --> 00:22:49.000
They'd be ready to go.

00:22:49.000 --> 00:22:55.000
And if a group, however many of them, they say they're going to be there in the morning and we're going,

00:22:55.000 --> 00:22:57.000
that's what they would do.

00:22:57.000 --> 00:22:59.000
Everybody would be ready to go.

00:22:59.000 --> 00:23:02.000
You hear lots of Turnbow stories.

00:23:02.000 --> 00:23:05.000
I heard one from Josephine Disparti.

00:23:05.000 --> 00:23:06.000
Do you remember her?

00:23:06.000 --> 00:23:07.000
Yes, yes.

00:23:07.000 --> 00:23:09.000
She was the nurse that she lived with Terinbo.

00:23:09.000 --> 00:23:10.000
Right.

00:23:10.000 --> 00:23:12.000
Yeah.

00:23:12.000 --> 00:23:18.000
She was saying that there was one meeting where there were all kinds of oppositions.

00:23:18.000 --> 00:23:25.000
And the one he was doing so at some point he gets out of his pistol and he's going to take a little sip of his bowl.

00:23:25.000 --> 00:23:28.000
Yes, he did.

00:23:28.000 --> 00:23:29.000
He did.

00:23:29.000 --> 00:23:36.000
He just, whatever he believed in and whatever he stood for, he did his whole heart and the 100%.

00:23:36.000 --> 00:23:39.000
He went scared of nobody.

00:23:39.000 --> 00:23:45.000
And he predicted all the things that we see now.

00:23:45.000 --> 00:23:50.000
He predicted all the things he used to come by my house and just sit and talk.

00:23:50.000 --> 00:23:54.000
After things had kind of quieted down some for years.

00:23:54.000 --> 00:23:58.000
He was getting older and he would tell me about what they'd expect.

00:23:58.000 --> 00:24:00.000
He said, I'll be gone.

00:24:00.000 --> 00:24:04.000
But he told me how many prisons was going up.

00:24:04.000 --> 00:24:08.000
And all that young black boys was going to be in those prisons.

00:24:08.000 --> 00:24:09.000
He saw that.

00:24:09.000 --> 00:24:10.000
He saw it.

00:24:10.000 --> 00:24:12.000
And it happened.

00:24:12.000 --> 00:24:14.000
Where are the things?

00:24:14.000 --> 00:24:16.000
Where are the things?

00:24:16.000 --> 00:24:18.000
The things was quiet.

00:24:18.000 --> 00:24:21.000
Kind of real man of man.

00:24:21.000 --> 00:24:25.000
And he thought he had to think things out completely before he would do anything.

00:24:25.000 --> 00:24:28.000
But he was always willing to do what he could.

00:24:28.000 --> 00:24:31.000
And he would try to help the rest of them to plan.

00:24:31.000 --> 00:24:37.000
So if there was something going on that he thought everybody might get locked up.

00:24:37.000 --> 00:24:44.000
He and a couple of other guys would stay back so that they could be there to help get them out of jail if they got locked up.

00:24:44.000 --> 00:24:50.000
So he was kind of a quiet person.

00:24:50.000 --> 00:24:53.000
But he was always willing to do things.

00:24:53.000 --> 00:24:55.000
A good farmer.

00:24:55.000 --> 00:24:59.000
So his personality was sort of the opposite of Mr. Hartman Turnbow.

00:24:59.000 --> 00:25:00.000
Just the opposite.

00:25:00.000 --> 00:25:04.000
And yet they were both leaders in that sense.

00:25:04.000 --> 00:25:06.000
What about statewide leaders?

00:25:06.000 --> 00:25:10.000
Did you go to meetings where Medgar Evers spoke?

00:25:10.000 --> 00:25:11.000
I did.

00:25:11.000 --> 00:25:12.000
Yeah.

00:25:12.000 --> 00:25:13.000
I did.

00:25:13.000 --> 00:25:18.000
And when you heard the news that he had been assassinated, what was going through?

00:25:18.000 --> 00:25:21.000
It was like a family member.

00:25:21.000 --> 00:25:23.000
It had been killed.

00:25:23.000 --> 00:25:29.000
Because we had been used to here and away off where they would lynch people.

00:25:29.000 --> 00:25:35.000
And they would burn their houses down, take over families.

00:25:35.000 --> 00:25:45.000
This guy told me I was working in the cat field, picking cat, and he told me about this white farmer head.

00:25:45.000 --> 00:25:53.000
Every time he, like he was being the house with his family, if it's one of the time they would do not do anything then.

00:25:53.000 --> 00:25:57.000
He said that that was the worst thing I've ever heard.

00:25:57.000 --> 00:26:07.000
He said that this farmer would come in his house and he would have to leave home and let him stay there and have his way with his wife.

00:26:07.000 --> 00:26:13.000
And he couldn't come back until he stayed with the time for him to come back.

00:26:13.000 --> 00:26:17.000
It's like Basin's flavor.

00:26:17.000 --> 00:26:22.000
But there was now a woman going on to do something about the air in memory.

00:26:22.000 --> 00:26:25.000
Someone was here around the mushroom.

00:26:25.000 --> 00:26:30.000
He came the whole time.

00:26:30.000 --> 00:26:36.000
Well let's talk a little bit about the Council of Federated Organizations.

00:26:36.000 --> 00:26:38.000
And we'll move up.

00:26:38.000 --> 00:26:42.000
I want to get into politics because you were very active there.

00:26:42.000 --> 00:26:49.000
But there was, for example, the Freedom vote in the fall of 63,

00:26:49.000 --> 00:26:53.000
where Aaron Henry and Ed King were running.

00:26:53.000 --> 00:27:01.000
And you've had a big campaign for a a mock election this to prove to the world that this is the big election vote given the chance.

00:27:01.000 --> 00:27:03.000
Were you active in that campaign?

00:27:03.000 --> 00:27:04.000
Yes, I was.

00:27:04.000 --> 00:27:06.000
Tell us about what you did.

00:27:06.000 --> 00:27:16.000
I went around canvassing the communities to get people, make sure people understood what the a mock election.

00:27:16.000 --> 00:27:21.000
And it was about how important it was to get out and come out and vote.

00:27:21.000 --> 00:27:29.000
And help out in the schools with the trained people what to do and how to do it.

00:27:29.000 --> 00:27:35.000
They come out and there was in kind of confrontation with the white folk.

00:27:35.000 --> 00:27:41.000
They would know what to do and not to get in the trouble.

00:27:41.000 --> 00:27:49.000
And we went all over Holmes County, all out in the heels, legs of the party, and do rent.

00:27:49.000 --> 00:27:56.000
And we are to get people to come out and register and try to vote.

00:27:56.000 --> 00:27:59.000
So I'm afraid even with the mock election to take the vote?

00:27:59.000 --> 00:28:05.000
Some are afraid because they were living in this plantation on this house that they were thinking.

00:28:05.000 --> 00:28:07.000
We would never place to live.

00:28:07.000 --> 00:28:13.000
Some people got put off the plantations and we had to find places where I was to live.

00:28:13.000 --> 00:28:20.000
And then there were people from the north that were sitting food and clothing and mining down.

00:28:20.000 --> 00:28:22.000
And we would help them out that way.

00:28:22.000 --> 00:28:27.000
But I remember several houses we had gone to.

00:28:27.000 --> 00:28:32.000
And we were then talking about head start trying to get head start.

00:28:32.000 --> 00:28:36.000
And we had to go to each house whether they accept us or not.

00:28:36.000 --> 00:28:39.000
And we would go to the white farm with houses.

00:28:39.000 --> 00:28:44.000
And they would always make you know you got to go to the back door.

00:28:44.000 --> 00:28:47.000
So they would either come out and curse you out.

00:28:47.000 --> 00:28:55.000
I'll say no you get that you couldn't go but they just say you can get out of my property and curse you out.

00:28:55.000 --> 00:28:57.000
And that was it.

00:28:57.000 --> 00:29:01.000
You were canvassing all the houses and talking about head start.

00:29:01.000 --> 00:29:05.000
It was supposed to be an integrated program.

00:29:05.000 --> 00:29:09.000
We had to do that to be able to get federal money.

00:29:09.000 --> 00:29:22.000
But for the election we just had to make sure we got everybody out and found out who needed a ride to come to vote in the mock election.

00:29:22.000 --> 00:29:25.000
Where were the polling places for the mock election?

00:29:25.000 --> 00:29:29.000
In Thornton and in Mileston.

00:29:29.000 --> 00:29:32.000
They were like all over the county.

00:29:32.000 --> 00:29:35.000
Were they in Barberjob, Beauty Barber?

00:29:35.000 --> 00:29:40.000
And then anybody had a place that had a place in the youth.

00:29:40.000 --> 00:29:44.000
So the vote set a message.

00:29:44.000 --> 00:29:53.000
But still at this time despite years of organizing why the white supremacists still have the upper hand.

00:29:53.000 --> 00:29:58.000
And the federal government wasn't really that interested in what was going on.

00:29:58.000 --> 00:30:00.000
It didn't seem to be interested.

00:30:00.000 --> 00:30:04.000
And the Ku Klux Klan had revived.

00:30:04.000 --> 00:30:07.000
Was there any clan activity in Holmes County?

00:30:07.000 --> 00:30:12.000
Oh yes. I can remember there were about six of us.

00:30:12.000 --> 00:30:21.000
We called it the Holmes County Community Center that Frian came down from California and deals for us.

00:30:21.000 --> 00:30:34.000
And we would all be there working late at night trying to get out of newsletters and get things ready to put in the mail for the next day.

00:30:34.000 --> 00:30:40.000
And several nights we would be just, there was a little sleeping quarters upstairs there.

00:30:40.000 --> 00:30:50.000
And we would be just getting settled down and we would hear the trucks out there making, turning around, around in the yard in front of the building.

00:30:50.000 --> 00:30:53.000
And then they would shoot up in there.

00:30:53.000 --> 00:30:56.000
And when we hear that, you know, it was just scared of us there.

00:30:56.000 --> 00:31:00.000
And we would go and try to call some of the men to come.

00:31:00.000 --> 00:31:04.000
And they would just continue.

00:31:04.000 --> 00:31:11.000
They would be shouting all kinds of language out at us and telling us to get out of that and what they would do to us.

00:31:11.000 --> 00:31:17.000
And by the time they see, we would like to send a set across railroad track.

00:31:17.000 --> 00:31:20.000
And we could see every car that turned off.

00:31:20.000 --> 00:31:27.000
By the time they see somebody coming that way, they would set the crawls out there and get back in the truck.

00:31:27.000 --> 00:31:31.000
And then like the crawls would shoot up in there and leave.

00:31:31.000 --> 00:31:34.000
And all intimidation.

00:31:34.000 --> 00:31:37.000
So you really were living with a fear of going on?

00:31:37.000 --> 00:31:46.000
All the time, even like when I would go home, I would, the adults would take turns sitting up watching the makes you.

00:31:46.000 --> 00:31:51.000
Of course, they were famous for throwing those what he called cocktails.

00:31:51.000 --> 00:31:54.000
Yeah, they would throw them in people's houses.

00:31:54.000 --> 00:31:57.000
How did you overcome your fear?

00:31:57.000 --> 00:32:04.000
Just praying and knowing that it was nothing else to do, you couldn't go back.

00:32:05.000 --> 00:32:16.000
Well, because things seemed to be still in the hands of the White Power structure without any assistance from outside,

00:32:16.000 --> 00:32:24.000
there was a decision made to have a summer project in 1964, bringing hundreds of students down to the North,

00:32:24.000 --> 00:32:31.000
most of whom turned out to be white, to really shine the spotlight on Mississippi.

00:32:31.000 --> 00:32:35.000
And to get the nation outraged about what was going on.

00:32:35.000 --> 00:32:43.000
And they'll be working in freedom schools, voter registration, the new Freedom Democratic Party, which we'll be talking about.

00:32:43.000 --> 00:32:47.000
And also in community centers.

00:32:47.000 --> 00:32:53.000
There were, they are, I read where there are about 30 Freedom Summer volunteers in Holmes County.

00:32:53.000 --> 00:32:58.000
Tell us about what Freedom Summer was like here in your role.

00:32:59.000 --> 00:33:06.000
It was like I spent most of my almost 24 hours a day in that deal.

00:33:06.000 --> 00:33:16.000
And with those people doing whatever it was to do, we would just be planning the way who was going where

00:33:16.000 --> 00:33:25.000
and what we had to do to get people to come out and learn how to go and try to register.

00:33:25.000 --> 00:33:32.000
And we would all get together and get in no call, whatever call we could find and go around campus in the community.

00:33:32.000 --> 00:33:37.000
That was the most we did, we were campus to get people out.

00:33:37.000 --> 00:33:45.000
And we would have meetings in different communities to talk to people so that they would understand and wouldn't be scared to come out.

00:33:45.000 --> 00:33:54.000
And we let them know that we all would be in it together, whatever happened, we was going to help them out of it.

00:33:54.000 --> 00:33:59.000
They didn't have a place to stay, that's what we were going to be able to help them when we were at them.

00:33:59.000 --> 00:34:02.000
So the volunteers were staying with local people?

00:34:02.000 --> 00:34:04.000
Local people, yes.

00:34:04.000 --> 00:34:08.000
How did Wines Free Act, this invasion as they go?

00:34:08.000 --> 00:34:17.000
Sometimes we would go downtown or some in the public place and they would just stand around just like, you know, they would be talking screaming out,

00:34:17.000 --> 00:34:22.000
you know, niggas, they had to do anything and calling them niggas levels.

00:34:22.000 --> 00:34:33.000
I never forget, we went to, we walked from Valley State from over here to being to Jackson.

00:34:33.000 --> 00:34:39.000
And there were people who left to that railroad to go down the state street.

00:34:39.000 --> 00:34:46.000
There were people on those railroads up on those box cars and they were throwing big rocks down there.

00:34:46.000 --> 00:34:51.000
They were just doing it enough for it not to hit you, but they wouldn't know if it was going to hit you.

00:34:51.000 --> 00:35:00.000
And I had gone, they had everything and they were calling us some of everything and the police men and highway patrol were right there, but they didn't say it was.

00:35:00.000 --> 00:35:02.000
Was this during a murder of the parks?

00:35:02.000 --> 00:35:05.000
Yes, yes.

00:35:05.000 --> 00:35:13.000
Were there any extreme racial incidents in Holmes County during Freedom Summer?

00:35:13.000 --> 00:35:17.000
Do you remember people playing arresting them?

00:35:17.000 --> 00:35:20.000
Yes, that was Sam House.

00:35:20.000 --> 00:35:22.000
He got arrested several times.

00:35:22.000 --> 00:35:27.000
They had this black guy in Lexington, we call him Fett.

00:35:27.000 --> 00:35:33.000
He would, if they just walked down the streets, he would pick him up and put him into here.

00:35:33.000 --> 00:35:40.000
And there was a lot of time that they got, we were marching and they would come out upset about it.

00:35:40.000 --> 00:35:45.000
We would be marching because we would boycott and some stores out there.

00:35:45.000 --> 00:36:00.000
And there was a time when this lady that they had taken her bag, she would not leave and just pull her down and expose her old body to everybody.

00:36:00.000 --> 00:36:10.000
One of the things that was going on that summer, I mean, Holmes County was unique in many ways in terms of the Civil Rights Movement.

00:36:10.000 --> 00:36:23.000
But a guy from California named Abe Osheroff came down to build the Mileston Community Center and tell us about what that was like from your ad seeing these strange folks out there going to work.

00:36:23.000 --> 00:36:25.000
We couldn't believe it.

00:36:25.000 --> 00:36:36.000
Someone would come and give us a whole new bill and like, my dad helped to build the center and he abled the good man and a real kind hearted.

00:36:36.000 --> 00:36:42.000
He looked big and seriously, but he was a real kind hearted man.

00:36:42.000 --> 00:36:45.000
We got to be real good friends.

00:36:45.000 --> 00:36:54.000
Seeing that Bill and go up, people would come from all over the county and just stand around and watch things being done.

00:36:54.000 --> 00:37:05.000
And when the building the guy finished with the building they couldn't get the gas company to put gas in, they couldn't get a telephone.

00:37:05.000 --> 00:37:13.000
And we had to have wood heaters that we put up in the building they said, I think they were so much dope.

00:37:13.000 --> 00:37:19.000
And they did some of everything to scare us out of there.

00:37:19.000 --> 00:37:25.000
They were right from the highway over there. You probably came up through Mileston.

00:37:25.000 --> 00:37:42.000
They had to come across the railroad to get over there and they would keep one or two highway patrol and sit in there stopping everybody to come through so that they let people know not to try to come through because you would get a ticket and get your license taken away from them.

00:37:42.000 --> 00:37:51.000
So in the same way, people going to Tougaloo sometimes and they can stop saying, go move there.

00:37:51.000 --> 00:37:57.000
That fall, a couple of new people came to town, Henry and Sue and Lorenzi.

00:37:57.000 --> 00:37:58.000
Yes.

00:37:58.000 --> 00:38:01.000
They lived in the center for a little while.

00:38:01.000 --> 00:38:06.000
They talk about Sue + Henry then when I'm going to talk about your work at the center.

00:38:06.000 --> 00:38:15.000
Sue + Henry, when they came in, they were different for sure whether it was going to stay here.

00:38:15.000 --> 00:38:26.000
And they got to know some of the people there and realized what we had and what we needed then they decided to stay.

00:38:26.000 --> 00:38:30.000
And everybody kind of took a liking to Sue + Henry.

00:38:30.000 --> 00:38:37.000
Everybody would all come out to the center every day just to talk to Henry and Sue.

00:38:37.000 --> 00:38:44.000
And they were always Henry was the one that looked like he had all of them out of the head and asked us everything he came up with.

00:38:44.000 --> 00:38:53.000
He had asked me about working in the center, managing the community center when they were getting ready to leave.

00:38:53.000 --> 00:38:56.000
I was telling them I didn't have no skills for that.

00:38:56.000 --> 00:38:59.000
I didn't know how I would do anything like that.

00:38:59.000 --> 00:39:08.000
And he was telling me all the things that I had that I didn't know if he went down the line telling me about what I had did for him since he had been there.

00:39:08.000 --> 00:39:13.000
And he was telling me that I always told me I need to write a book.

00:39:13.000 --> 00:39:15.000
And I never did.

00:39:15.000 --> 00:39:17.000
Henry was a good man.

00:39:17.000 --> 00:39:21.000
We always tried to help the Arnold off.

00:39:21.000 --> 00:39:24.000
He felt needed to the mostly.

00:39:24.000 --> 00:39:33.000
He would let it be known that these other people you need to be looking to do things for and try to encourage them.

00:39:33.000 --> 00:39:40.000
But Henry and Sue did a lot to organize our community and all over the county.

00:39:40.000 --> 00:39:43.000
They finally eventually moved over in Lexington.

00:39:43.000 --> 00:39:50.000
But they were always coming back over and doing things to keep people together.

00:39:50.000 --> 00:39:54.000
And he asked you to run the center and you did.

00:39:54.000 --> 00:40:00.000
Now I want you to spend a little bit of time talking about your work there.

00:40:00.000 --> 00:40:07.000
Because lots of people read about community centers but they don't have the following idea of what their purpose was.

00:40:07.000 --> 00:40:16.000
So tell us about the milestone center and what services it provided and what kind of work you were doing.

00:40:16.000 --> 00:40:29.000
The main purpose of the center was to have a place for people to meet and to come together and talk about their problems of what they probably were in the county

00:40:29.000 --> 00:40:32.000
or what we could do to make it better.

00:40:32.000 --> 00:40:43.000
And it was like what I did was to keep all the records of everything they went on in the area in the county.

00:40:43.000 --> 00:40:51.000
And I was like to take all the messages coming in from wherever, even out of the state and everywhere.

00:40:51.000 --> 00:40:53.000
And sending newsletters out.

00:40:53.000 --> 00:40:57.000
And that was about four other young women working with me.

00:40:57.000 --> 00:41:05.000
And I was just in charge of making sure that everything, there was a record kept for everything.

00:41:05.000 --> 00:41:17.000
And that everything was in the center that needed to be there, everything that we needed to keep to be on and running was there.

00:41:17.000 --> 00:41:25.000
I had, I would call people and inform them about meetings of whatever was going on across the county.

00:41:25.000 --> 00:41:34.000
I would get out newsletters and also send notices to people that let them know things that were going on in the county.

00:41:34.000 --> 00:41:36.000
What was the cost of the county?

00:41:36.000 --> 00:41:42.000
Well, that was like you spoke of Josephine Disparti and there was another lady.

00:41:42.000 --> 00:41:44.000
Her name was Helen, I believe.

00:41:44.000 --> 00:41:46.000
Helen Richardson?

00:41:46.000 --> 00:41:51.000
And Helen, you mean there was another guy on the way.

00:41:51.000 --> 00:41:58.000
And they came first just in the center they would help out.

00:41:58.000 --> 00:42:06.000
They gave people physical exams and everything and whatever medical services they could bring that they did.

00:42:06.000 --> 00:42:10.000
And we found a way to get a little room built for the clinic.

00:42:10.000 --> 00:42:16.000
And they started letting people come from all over the county just like a regular doctor's office.

00:42:16.000 --> 00:42:20.000
And they stayed there.

00:42:20.000 --> 00:42:23.000
At least I know all that summer.

00:42:23.000 --> 00:42:31.000
And they would come back once in a while but they offered medical services to the county.

00:42:31.000 --> 00:42:36.000
And there were the medical committee for human rights organization running into them.

00:42:36.000 --> 00:42:39.000
Young doctor named Albert Versailles.

00:42:39.000 --> 00:42:41.000
I knew him well.

00:42:41.000 --> 00:42:47.000
In fact he used to stay in touch with me a lot.

00:42:47.000 --> 00:42:49.000
Yes.

00:42:49.000 --> 00:43:04.000
But I think people, movement, comprehensive community health centers which provide health care to over 30 million Americans now that all started in that little clinic in milestone.

00:43:04.000 --> 00:43:13.000
From there they got the idea to expand and open health centers here in America.

00:43:13.000 --> 00:43:16.000
How do they operate?

00:43:16.000 --> 00:43:23.000
There are several medical clinics for their school out there.

00:43:23.000 --> 00:43:26.000
There was a name for this doctor, a renacy maler.

00:43:26.000 --> 00:43:29.000
And they had those clinics in a lot of times.

00:43:29.000 --> 00:43:35.000
And they offered services to people they can't afford regular doctors.

00:43:35.000 --> 00:43:41.000
They free-service to some people and some people you pay as you're able to.

00:43:41.000 --> 00:43:48.000
So was health care improved around here from the time that you were sick on the plantation?

00:43:48.000 --> 00:43:50.000
What did you do?

00:43:50.000 --> 00:43:52.000
Take home remedies.

00:43:52.000 --> 00:43:54.000
Did you ever see a doctor?

00:43:54.000 --> 00:43:59.000
I had never seen a doctor until I had my first child.

00:43:59.000 --> 00:44:00.000
Or been in a hospital?

00:44:00.000 --> 00:44:01.000
Never.

00:44:01.000 --> 00:44:03.000
And the rest of your family did they?

00:44:03.000 --> 00:44:04.000
Never.

00:44:04.000 --> 00:44:06.000
Because they'd have to take.

00:44:06.000 --> 00:44:10.000
And my mom had all of us at home.

00:44:10.000 --> 00:44:14.000
And there were no black doctors in the county.

00:44:14.000 --> 00:44:16.000
No.

00:44:16.000 --> 00:44:21.000
So there have been some changes there.

00:44:21.000 --> 00:44:26.000
Other, you're far too modest about your work in the center.

00:44:26.000 --> 00:44:34.000
I have something here that says you handle day-to-day center programs for kids.

00:44:34.000 --> 00:44:35.000
A kindergarten?

00:44:35.000 --> 00:44:36.000
Oh, yeah.

00:44:36.000 --> 00:44:38.000
I'm thinking of getting about his idea.

00:44:38.000 --> 00:44:45.000
We did the two years before we got federal money we had.

00:44:45.000 --> 00:44:53.000
We had decided that we wanted to open a school for kindergarten.

00:44:53.000 --> 00:44:56.000
We didn't have a kindergarten at the time.

00:44:56.000 --> 00:44:58.000
And they were kindergarten age children.

00:44:58.000 --> 00:45:07.000
So with the help of Sue + Henry, we set up a makeshift school for children to come

00:45:07.000 --> 00:45:12.000
and we went around in Kansas to see what children we could get to come.

00:45:12.000 --> 00:45:19.000
And we had Abe also gave us a truck when we went to build a center.

00:45:19.000 --> 00:45:25.000
And we could finally learn how to drive it well enough that we would go around and pick up all the children

00:45:25.000 --> 00:45:28.000
and bring them to school and keep them there.

00:45:28.000 --> 00:45:30.000
I'm telling them 330 in the evening.

00:45:30.000 --> 00:45:33.000
We would feed them.

00:45:34.000 --> 00:45:40.000
In the morning time we would have stuff like grits, oatmeal, milk and cookies or whatever we could get.

00:45:40.000 --> 00:45:46.000
And the different farmers would give us things, different items to help out.

00:45:46.000 --> 00:45:52.000
And they would give us money for kids or either they would give us kids, put kids in the truck from their farming kids.

00:45:52.000 --> 00:45:56.000
And we would go around and pick the children up and bring them back.

00:45:56.000 --> 00:45:58.000
And we would do all kind of things.

00:45:58.000 --> 00:46:00.000
We made clothes for them.

00:46:00.000 --> 00:46:02.000
We had sewing machines and I assisted me.

00:46:02.000 --> 00:46:06.000
We had a soul of this and we made clothes for all the children.

00:46:06.000 --> 00:46:13.000
And we would go through all kind of activities.

00:46:13.000 --> 00:46:17.000
We had farmers to come out and play around and quit.

00:46:17.000 --> 00:46:23.000
And we just did everything that you were doing at school with the help of Sue + Henry.

00:46:23.000 --> 00:46:25.000
Now this was before he had started.

00:46:25.000 --> 00:46:28.000
He was basically everything.

00:46:28.000 --> 00:46:34.000
And sometimes I think it was better then because you could do what you wanted to have all these rules.

00:46:34.000 --> 00:46:36.000
Did that reinforce the gun?

00:46:36.000 --> 00:46:39.000
It was a good problem for people.

00:46:39.000 --> 00:46:41.000
Everybody was children now.

00:46:41.000 --> 00:46:47.000
Sometimes they come by and they won the boy I never forget.

00:46:47.000 --> 00:46:49.000
We all called him short.

00:46:49.000 --> 00:46:55.000
And he said, the first day he came to school and he cried so hard not to come.

00:46:55.000 --> 00:46:57.000
And we came and picked him up anyway.

00:46:57.000 --> 00:46:59.000
And he went back on with his shoulders.

00:46:59.000 --> 00:47:03.000
Grandma, that's the best school in the world.

00:47:03.000 --> 00:47:07.000
Because they will feed you three meals every day you go to school.

00:47:07.000 --> 00:47:10.000
And then they'll let you lay down and go to sleep.

00:47:10.000 --> 00:47:13.000
And still bring you back home.

00:47:13.000 --> 00:47:17.000
And he said he told me he'll never forget that.

00:47:17.000 --> 00:47:20.000
And he said, I'm going to go with him and rest of the life.

00:47:20.000 --> 00:47:23.000
And he said every time he goes somewhere they start talking.

00:47:23.000 --> 00:47:26.000
And some people talk about their first teachers.

00:47:26.000 --> 00:47:30.000
And he would go back and call my name and think about all the times.

00:47:30.000 --> 00:47:35.000
That when he was scared and nervous I would let him lay on my lap and rock him in the little rock.

00:47:35.000 --> 00:47:37.000
And he said, I was at home.

00:47:37.000 --> 00:47:39.000
I had two grandbots.

00:47:39.000 --> 00:47:43.000
That was a good problem.

00:47:43.000 --> 00:47:46.000
I want to talk about your work in Head Start a little later.

00:47:46.000 --> 00:47:53.000
But now let's like to switch to another major area of your concern and activity.

00:47:53.000 --> 00:47:56.000
And that is voting in elections.

00:47:56.000 --> 00:48:07.000
And what you have is a county that has majority black, very few blacks voting.

00:48:07.000 --> 00:48:15.000
And this you have we talked about trying to register in April of 1963.

00:48:15.000 --> 00:48:21.000
And then in 1965 the voting rights act was passed.

00:48:21.000 --> 00:48:25.000
And federal registrars came in.

00:48:25.000 --> 00:48:30.000
And how did you take advantage of this?

00:48:30.000 --> 00:48:38.000
The federal registrars came and we had tried to go out and register.

00:48:38.000 --> 00:48:40.000
And we were blocked from that.

00:48:40.000 --> 00:48:45.000
In fact, we were taking a lot of people out all the time.

00:48:45.000 --> 00:48:49.000
And when I first went out there were five of us winning.

00:48:49.000 --> 00:48:57.000
And when we went up to the courthouse and the sheriff knew that we were there,

00:48:57.000 --> 00:49:06.000
all his debuts just came out with the dogs and the clubs and the guns and everything.

00:49:06.000 --> 00:49:10.000
And I was real nervous because I'm afraid of dogs.

00:49:10.000 --> 00:49:14.000
They would walk right along the side.

00:49:14.000 --> 00:49:17.000
And let the dog be between them and you.

00:49:17.000 --> 00:49:22.000
And then when they go, they'd pull them back just a little bit, but they would come back again.

00:49:22.000 --> 00:49:26.000
I never forget when I went, when I finally went in,

00:49:26.000 --> 00:49:31.000
they put me in a little room like a closet with a little desk in it.

00:49:31.000 --> 00:49:33.000
They closed the door.

00:49:33.000 --> 00:49:36.000
And I'd been in there by now.

00:49:36.000 --> 00:49:41.000
And I had finished, been finished with that feeling out the paper.

00:49:41.000 --> 00:49:48.000
I tried to open the door and when I touched the door knob, I heard the dog growling.

00:49:48.000 --> 00:49:51.000
I said, oh my god.

00:49:51.000 --> 00:49:54.000
Every time I was touched the door, he was proud.

00:49:54.000 --> 00:49:57.000
So they had left him there, guarding the door.

00:49:57.000 --> 00:50:02.000
And it was about four hours later when they came and let me out.

00:50:02.000 --> 00:50:05.000
And I was scared to death.

00:50:05.000 --> 00:50:07.000
So you were held as a prisoner?

00:50:07.000 --> 00:50:11.000
Because I was thinking if I come out, you'd definitely going to take me.

00:50:11.000 --> 00:50:13.000
That's the story I've never heard of.

00:50:13.000 --> 00:50:15.000
All kinds of intimidation.

00:50:15.000 --> 00:50:18.000
That's what they do.

00:50:18.000 --> 00:50:30.000
And the Chancellor Clerk had said to me, now I know you know that he knew my grandparent.

00:50:30.000 --> 00:50:35.000
I've known your people for years and years and I know you know better.

00:50:35.000 --> 00:50:37.000
What are you doing out here anyway?

00:50:37.000 --> 00:50:40.000
And so I told him what I wanted.

00:50:40.000 --> 00:50:43.000
And he said, you go home and do like your mom and your grandmom did.

00:50:43.000 --> 00:50:45.000
You don't need to come out here.

00:50:46.000 --> 00:50:48.000
And they were all waiting for black folk.

00:50:48.000 --> 00:50:51.000
That's the way they did.

00:50:51.000 --> 00:50:54.000
All of us, they went for a later day when we were mean.

00:50:54.000 --> 00:50:58.000
And we were able to go back a second day for some of us.

00:50:58.000 --> 00:51:02.000
And we all went together because we knew how it was.

00:51:02.000 --> 00:51:09.000
But they never told us that we had passed the test until the federal regressive came.

00:51:09.000 --> 00:51:11.000
And they found the records and everything.

00:51:11.000 --> 00:51:14.000
And they had passed the test until the next year.

00:51:14.000 --> 00:51:17.000
And they finally told us that we had passed the same, which time we had gone out there.

00:51:17.000 --> 00:51:19.000
But they did, you passed it, but they didn't tell us.

00:51:19.000 --> 00:51:20.000
They didn't tell us.

00:51:20.000 --> 00:51:25.000
They were supposed to send you a letter or a notify you that they didn't tell us.

00:51:25.000 --> 00:51:29.000
So it really took real courage before the voting rights act.

00:51:29.000 --> 00:51:32.000
I always tried to register.

00:51:32.000 --> 00:51:38.000
And then the voting rights act is passed and the federal registrar has come in.

00:51:38.000 --> 00:51:41.000
And it's a lot easier, isn't it?

00:51:41.000 --> 00:51:47.000
And now how did you get folks who had been afraid to vote to register before saying it's okay now?

00:51:47.000 --> 00:51:50.000
What did you do to get them to the registrar?

00:51:50.000 --> 00:51:54.000
They started it after they saw so many people.

00:51:54.000 --> 00:52:00.000
And then the main thing was when they started to see that there were houses available for them.

00:52:00.000 --> 00:52:02.000
And they get put out the plantation.

00:52:02.000 --> 00:52:07.000
They were afraid of not having a place to live.

00:52:07.000 --> 00:52:10.000
And so other people gone.

00:52:10.000 --> 00:52:15.000
Sometimes we would just get truckloads of people all in the back of the truck and take them out there.

00:52:15.000 --> 00:52:17.000
And you had to take them.

00:52:17.000 --> 00:52:20.000
Most people wouldn't just go on their own.

00:52:20.000 --> 00:52:28.000
Somebody had to be with them, just like they just think that they had protection.

00:52:28.000 --> 00:52:31.000
And it took a lot of talking.

00:52:31.000 --> 00:52:35.000
A lot of people said they were gone and didn't have a long time.

00:52:35.000 --> 00:52:38.000
And they all got a little better.

00:52:38.000 --> 00:52:41.000
And they knew that everybody was doing it.

00:52:41.000 --> 00:52:44.000
And if I hadn't started coming out.

00:52:44.000 --> 00:52:49.000
One of the things that it was notable, I think, throughout the state.

00:52:49.000 --> 00:52:56.000
And throughout the South is that at the beginning, the early stages of the civil rights movement,

00:52:56.000 --> 00:53:04.000
black professionals, the teachers and preachers were not around very much worth it.

00:53:04.000 --> 00:53:09.000
Why was that?

00:53:09.000 --> 00:53:16.000
I think most of them thought that they stood in good with their white folk.

00:53:16.000 --> 00:53:24.000
And they didn't want them to think they were doing that because they were telling them that they were some crazy white folks coming in here.

00:53:24.000 --> 00:53:28.000
Some eyesight agitators and educated people.

00:53:28.000 --> 00:53:31.000
And people like them weren't supposed to be.

00:53:31.000 --> 00:53:34.000
But I think they were mostly scared and they were good at it.

00:53:34.000 --> 00:53:38.000
They had behind some of the teachers thinking they would lose their job.

00:53:38.000 --> 00:53:41.000
Because Bernice Montgomery is from the beginning.

00:53:41.000 --> 00:53:47.000
She came down with us and she would come to my house and put all the meetings.

00:53:47.000 --> 00:53:50.000
She was a teacher.

00:53:50.000 --> 00:53:52.000
It's sort of still out.

00:53:52.000 --> 00:53:55.000
Yeah, she came right away.

00:53:56.000 --> 00:54:02.000
It took a lot of talking and coaxing and had the meetings and everything.

00:54:02.000 --> 00:54:04.000
They would come to the meetings.

00:54:04.000 --> 00:54:10.000
Some of them were coming because it was night and they thought nobody knew they were there.

00:54:10.000 --> 00:54:11.000
They were coming.

00:54:11.000 --> 00:54:17.000
And they saw everybody else voting and they just sat and come on out.

00:54:17.000 --> 00:54:23.000
So you got a lot of people registered and then it was time to start planning for elections.

00:54:24.000 --> 00:54:26.000
I was reading and Sue's book.

00:54:26.000 --> 00:54:32.000
You were very active in a 1966 election for congressional races.

00:54:32.000 --> 00:54:34.000
Mr. Hayes running here.

00:54:34.000 --> 00:54:39.000
What did you do to mobilize people for that election?

00:54:39.000 --> 00:54:48.000
We had different, like we had a lot of people that had a car to agree to, you know, we give gas to them.

00:54:48.000 --> 00:54:50.000
That's traveling.

00:54:50.000 --> 00:54:52.000
We agreed to pick up people that needed.

00:54:52.000 --> 00:54:55.000
We had people posted at the center.

00:54:55.000 --> 00:54:59.000
They could take calls when there were some people needing to be picked up.

00:54:59.000 --> 00:55:02.000
And they called all over the county.

00:55:02.000 --> 00:55:11.000
They were going and picking people up and getting them to the polls and waiting and taking them back home and everything.

00:55:11.000 --> 00:55:19.000
But we had to let them know a head of time, you know, that we had transportation available to them.

00:55:19.000 --> 00:55:31.000
And we had to have somebody for each area to find out how many people there needed to go and how many were willing to go.

00:55:31.000 --> 00:55:35.000
Because most of them were afraid so you had to go and get them.

00:55:35.000 --> 00:55:36.000
They wouldn't just come.

00:55:36.000 --> 00:55:38.000
Some people made a way of calling.

00:55:38.000 --> 00:55:41.000
But they didn't, they were afraid to come on their own.

00:55:41.000 --> 00:55:49.000
So we had to make sure that they knew that we were with them and we were coming to pick them up.

00:55:49.000 --> 00:55:55.000
And I should have pointed out that this was all under the offices of the Mississippi Freedom Democratic Party.

00:55:55.000 --> 00:55:59.000
It was not, you were not part of the right-winged Democratic Party.

00:55:59.000 --> 00:56:04.000
Talk about your early work with the Freedom Democrats.

00:56:04.000 --> 00:56:10.000
We had different people in the county and different parts of the county.

00:56:10.000 --> 00:56:15.000
They were in charge of their area.

00:56:15.000 --> 00:56:19.000
And the people in the community just knew who to get in touch with.

00:56:19.000 --> 00:56:21.000
They were like, they called in.

00:56:21.000 --> 00:56:29.000
They were telling you to tell them who they could get in touch with and who was being able to that day.

00:56:29.000 --> 00:56:35.000
And before we had all kinds of meetings all across the county telling them who we were going to do and where we were going to be.

00:56:35.000 --> 00:56:37.000
And who was going to do what?

00:56:37.000 --> 00:56:48.000
So we had to get organized for that just like the real Democratic Party.

00:56:48.000 --> 00:56:58.000
We had people all over the county and then placed for people to get information from to know what to do and everything.

00:56:58.000 --> 00:57:08.000
And then take them to the polling places and let them know that these people, someone would even be afraid to go and say what they wanted to do.

00:57:08.000 --> 00:57:11.000
Which you had to go and just talk for them.

00:57:11.000 --> 00:57:14.000
For someone who had to speak for all of them.

00:57:14.000 --> 00:57:18.000
In those early elections, was there intimidation at the polls?

00:57:18.000 --> 00:57:19.000
Oh yes.

00:57:19.000 --> 00:57:24.000
I had an instance where this guy wanted to...

00:57:24.000 --> 00:57:29.000
His wife had never worked at the polls and I was the manager.

00:57:29.000 --> 00:57:33.000
And the receiving and the returning manager.

00:57:33.000 --> 00:57:37.000
And the chance to be cleared.

00:57:37.000 --> 00:57:42.000
Then the circuit clerk, that's the world to care about more.

00:57:42.000 --> 00:57:49.000
He had agreed to let this woman work in the position that I had had before.

00:57:49.000 --> 00:57:59.000
And then he called me at home one night to tell me that he expected me to do what I had been doing all the time because she was new and she wouldn't know.

00:57:59.000 --> 00:58:04.000
And I asked him who was going to be caring that title and be responsible for the election.

00:58:04.000 --> 00:58:09.000
He said she was and I said, well all right, that's what she would be doing.

00:58:09.000 --> 00:58:11.000
So I won't be doing it. She would be doing it.

00:58:11.000 --> 00:58:14.000
So he came down that day.

00:58:14.000 --> 00:58:18.000
And because she told him that she couldn't do it.

00:58:18.000 --> 00:58:22.000
She didn't understand that she couldn't do it. She would rather not.

00:58:22.000 --> 00:58:27.000
I also was put back in that position to be in receiving and returning and men.

00:58:27.000 --> 00:58:31.000
And that even in her home was a truck drive.

00:58:31.000 --> 00:58:38.000
He had a big log truck that even he came and somebody told him that his wife would work in that position.

00:58:38.000 --> 00:58:43.000
So he came out there. He had been drinking and he was cursing everybody out.

00:58:43.000 --> 00:58:48.000
He was just going to take her out and take her home and she wouldn't ever come back down that game.

00:58:48.000 --> 00:58:54.000
So he had gone and everything. But some of our people came in and got him out of there.

00:58:54.000 --> 00:58:55.000
And he got caught.

00:58:55.000 --> 00:58:59.000
It was a little kind of scary at first though. He was the only one who got gone in there.

00:58:59.000 --> 00:59:01.000
And he was crazy because he was drunk.

00:59:01.000 --> 00:59:05.000
And he came and took it out of there.

00:59:05.000 --> 00:59:09.000
And she couldn't help us to close the election.

00:59:09.000 --> 00:59:14.000
I remember back then we had old buildings.

00:59:14.000 --> 00:59:16.000
We had to vote in.

00:59:16.000 --> 00:59:19.000
And sometimes the heat wasn't good.

00:59:19.000 --> 00:59:21.000
It would be so cold in there.

00:59:21.000 --> 00:59:26.000
And we have stayed there from then we went in at 6.30.

00:59:26.000 --> 00:59:33.000
And we had to tell three and four o'clock that next morning we had to count them through the talent.

00:59:33.000 --> 00:59:35.000
And that was rough.

00:59:35.000 --> 00:59:37.000
We had to stick it out.

00:59:37.000 --> 00:59:38.000
There were several of us.

00:59:38.000 --> 00:59:42.000
And the other people would come in just to be there for support.

00:59:42.000 --> 00:59:46.000
They could stand around. They just couldn't in the field with the elections.

00:59:46.000 --> 00:59:54.000
I would bring in the community that would come out because it would be some of them there and some of us.

00:59:54.000 --> 00:59:57.000
And it would be rough.

00:59:57.000 --> 01:00:03.000
I remember well from my own experience and from others that on an election day,

01:00:03.000 --> 01:00:09.000
why very often really rough looking white people with park themselves right in front of the door.

01:00:09.000 --> 01:00:12.000
I wouldn't say anything they just sit there.

01:00:12.000 --> 01:00:17.000
I was doing some full watching in Canton and cars with black families,

01:00:17.000 --> 01:00:19.000
with black boards with cars.

01:00:19.000 --> 01:00:22.000
And they'd see these guys and they'd turn off and go away.

01:00:22.000 --> 01:00:25.000
That's what they were doing.

01:00:25.000 --> 01:00:31.000
When time came for you to do the talent, they would come and stand right.

01:00:31.000 --> 01:00:35.000
They could be able to observe you looking over your shoulder and everything.

01:00:35.000 --> 01:00:39.000
So they would come and they wouldn't see anything.

01:00:39.000 --> 01:00:42.000
But they would just come and act like we would.

01:00:42.000 --> 01:00:48.000
When you had voters who had trouble reading, how did you handle that?

01:00:48.000 --> 01:00:51.000
Were you able to go into the polling booth with them?

01:00:51.000 --> 01:00:52.000
Yes.

01:00:52.000 --> 01:00:57.000
How were they able to catch their vote the way they wanted to?

01:00:57.000 --> 01:01:03.000
We had to make sure they knew that there were people there that they could ask for help.

01:01:03.000 --> 01:01:06.000
That we couldn't just come and do and help them.

01:01:06.000 --> 01:01:09.000
But there were people there that they could ask for help.

01:01:09.000 --> 01:01:15.000
It got so many people would ask me to help them.

01:01:16.000 --> 01:01:21.000
The other side started saying that I didn't want me to work at the polls.

01:01:21.000 --> 01:01:26.000
They were thinking I was doing something because I would everybody knows to ask me.

01:01:26.000 --> 01:01:30.000
But see, that was just the communication we had before.

01:01:30.000 --> 01:01:33.000
You had to really be set up.

01:01:33.000 --> 01:01:35.000
They would.

01:01:35.000 --> 01:01:37.000
They would say, I can't do this.

01:01:37.000 --> 01:01:38.000
I don't understand.

01:01:38.000 --> 01:01:41.000
And they just, someone would come out of it.

01:01:42.000 --> 01:01:51.000
They would come in and I would really forget they later came and she had, when she came in the door, she had asked for me.

01:01:51.000 --> 01:01:54.000
They would want to know what she was wondering with me and who I was.

01:01:54.000 --> 01:01:59.000
She was asking for a poll and she said, whether they had trouble.

01:01:59.000 --> 01:02:03.000
She said, I was told that she could help me.

01:02:03.000 --> 01:02:04.000
I don't know how to vote.

01:02:04.000 --> 01:02:06.000
She can help me.

01:02:07.000 --> 01:02:12.000
So this white guy, the name of Bob and Liz, he told she couldn't vote that day.

01:02:12.000 --> 01:02:14.000
She didn't know how she couldn't vote.

01:02:14.000 --> 01:02:17.000
And so one of the poll voices happened here.

01:02:17.000 --> 01:02:19.000
So he brought over that and told them.

01:02:19.000 --> 01:02:22.000
He got real upset.

01:02:22.000 --> 01:02:25.000
And the lady, his wife worked at the welfare office.

01:02:25.000 --> 01:02:30.000
And the lady was getting food stamps and welfare check.

01:02:30.000 --> 01:02:34.000
They cut her house to her because it's all benefit.

01:02:34.000 --> 01:02:37.000
And she could get it straight now.

01:02:37.000 --> 01:02:43.000
In 1966 elections were sort of a warm up for the 67 elections.

01:02:43.000 --> 01:02:49.000
And this is if the off-year elections over all the local officials and state legislators are elected.

01:02:49.000 --> 01:02:55.000
And this was a very big time in the Holmes County.

01:02:55.000 --> 01:02:58.000
Robert Clark was running for the state legislature.

01:02:58.000 --> 01:03:04.000
Tell us about Mr. Clark and why he was a good candidate and they saw why.

01:03:04.000 --> 01:03:10.000
He was well known all over the county.

01:03:10.000 --> 01:03:14.000
And he had been a school teacher before that.

01:03:14.000 --> 01:03:20.000
And he had gone around and did all of his campaign and then everything.

01:03:20.000 --> 01:03:22.000
And everybody knew him.

01:03:22.000 --> 01:03:27.000
And it was kind of where everybody knew what they was going to do when they went out there.

01:03:27.000 --> 01:03:31.000
They tried everything to scare people back.

01:03:31.000 --> 01:03:35.000
They had people out there working for them, the white folks,

01:03:35.000 --> 01:03:42.000
saying telling them people what's going to happen if they went out and tried to vote for Representative Clark.

01:03:42.000 --> 01:03:48.000
And there was a lot of people who would come back and report what they had said to them.

01:03:48.000 --> 01:03:54.000
So by us having somebody stationed at every place outside and inside,

01:03:55.000 --> 01:04:00.000
we had people out there that would be there to assist anybody that had trouble.

01:04:00.000 --> 01:04:05.000
They would make sure, because if a person coming up to vote, they wouldn't know who was who.

01:04:05.000 --> 01:04:09.000
They would even have some black people out there working for them.

01:04:09.000 --> 01:04:15.000
So we had to try to make sure that they knew that we were there and they even helped them.

01:04:15.000 --> 01:04:22.000
So it had gotten by then so that people knew what they was going to do with before they left home.

01:04:22.000 --> 01:04:26.000
And that's how we were successful in this area all the time,

01:04:26.000 --> 01:04:32.000
because people would always, if they knew that an election was coming up,

01:04:32.000 --> 01:04:38.000
they would call, either me or somebody else, to find out what candidates we support,

01:04:38.000 --> 01:04:40.000
and what are we doing now?

01:04:40.000 --> 01:04:42.000
Where is the day and where do we go?

01:04:42.000 --> 01:04:44.000
They would call and get all that information.

01:04:44.000 --> 01:04:50.000
And then we would tell that person, tell your neighbor, tell your sister, your brother,

01:04:50.000 --> 01:04:53.000
so they can know what to do when they get there.

01:04:53.000 --> 01:04:59.000
That was some of the ways that we always were able to do the word of mouth thing,

01:04:59.000 --> 01:05:02.000
and we couldn't count on getting to everybody, but we knew,

01:05:02.000 --> 01:05:05.000
we would always know somebody that knew the next person,

01:05:05.000 --> 01:05:09.000
and they would make sure they knew what to do.

01:05:09.000 --> 01:05:15.000
Lauren Skiyot and his prepist, the soldier of his book,

01:05:15.000 --> 01:05:19.000
was talking about Holmes County as being the best organized county in the state.

01:05:20.000 --> 01:05:23.000
And there were a number of other counties with black majorities,

01:05:23.000 --> 01:05:32.000
but in that election in 1967, the election of Robert Clark was the only successful legislative race,

01:05:32.000 --> 01:05:39.000
and Clark became the first African American to sit in the state legislature in the 20th century.

01:05:39.000 --> 01:05:42.000
Was there a big party after that election?

01:05:42.000 --> 01:05:45.000
Yes, all over the county state,

01:05:45.000 --> 01:05:49.000
people who ate yesterday were really proud.

01:05:49.000 --> 01:05:54.000
It made us, Robert Clark was, whatever,

01:05:54.000 --> 01:05:57.000
we're going on in the county.

01:05:57.000 --> 01:06:02.000
If Robert Clark approved it, we knew that's what we needed to do.

01:06:02.000 --> 01:06:12.000
We're going to, I would like them to look now at your professional career in Headstart,

01:06:12.000 --> 01:06:19.000
and talk about CDGM and how you got involved and how that operated.

01:06:19.000 --> 01:06:27.000
Well, CDGM and Sue and Hennie brought this to us also.

01:06:27.000 --> 01:06:40.000
The state had got funded for six weeks, and we had to get the people they wanted to work,

01:06:40.000 --> 01:06:47.000
and get a committee and everything to sit up for the center.

01:06:47.000 --> 01:06:54.000
And Mileston was the only center that, in that five, six week program,

01:06:54.000 --> 01:06:58.000
and we went down to Mount Bueblah, places.

01:06:58.000 --> 01:07:07.000
It was necessary for a week when we stayed there and got trained on what the government expected of us with that program.

01:07:07.000 --> 01:07:11.000
And it turned out just great.

01:07:11.000 --> 01:07:14.000
Everything worked out well.

01:07:14.000 --> 01:07:21.000
We thought we had it for just as long as we needed it.

01:07:21.000 --> 01:07:25.000
It was really a good program.

01:07:25.000 --> 01:07:32.000
I remember Polly Greenberg and Tom Levin,

01:07:32.000 --> 01:07:38.000
and we were along with the chairperson for our center.

01:07:38.000 --> 01:07:43.000
I was a secretary and I was also an assistant teacher.

01:07:43.000 --> 01:07:49.000
So we had to drive to Jackson, like every Friday.

01:07:49.000 --> 01:07:57.000
Like this Friday we carried the payroll and all the information to get what we needed for the center's operation of the center.

01:07:57.000 --> 01:07:59.000
And we'll take the paperwork down there.

01:07:59.000 --> 01:08:05.000
The next week we go and pick the checks up, and we had an account and a bank in Tchula,

01:08:05.000 --> 01:08:11.000
And in the beginning, the bank refused to cash out checks.

01:08:11.000 --> 01:08:14.000
They said they didn't know what it was. They had never heard of it.

01:08:14.000 --> 01:08:18.000
And the only way we got checks was cash.

01:08:18.000 --> 01:08:21.000
That was a supermarket in Tula.

01:08:21.000 --> 01:08:24.000
They were cashed out checks, but they wouldn't even cash the checks.

01:08:24.000 --> 01:08:26.000
The banks come around.

01:08:26.000 --> 01:08:30.000
They came around as a guy that had a supermarket, a blue hotel.

01:08:30.000 --> 01:08:33.000
He finally talked them into it.

01:08:33.000 --> 01:08:37.000
And I remember there was another guy's name with DC Cohen.

01:08:37.000 --> 01:08:40.000
They were talking about how was the fine going to come to us.

01:08:40.000 --> 01:08:43.000
And they wanted us to get committed.

01:08:43.000 --> 01:08:48.000
They'd then be over the fine and part of the program.

01:08:48.000 --> 01:08:51.000
And we refused that night to do that.

01:08:51.000 --> 01:08:54.000
And the club probably won't tell you all about it.

01:08:54.000 --> 01:08:55.000
So I let him do it.

01:08:55.000 --> 01:09:00.000
When we had that meeting that night, he thought I was from outside of Mississippi.

01:09:00.000 --> 01:09:02.000
I was asking some questions.

01:09:02.000 --> 01:09:06.000
But he'll tell you that he'd love to do that himself.

01:09:06.000 --> 01:09:13.000
But anyway, there was a guy that has a store in Lexington, a track list.

01:09:13.000 --> 01:09:15.000
So his name is Cohen.

01:09:15.000 --> 01:09:17.000
I remember him and Hayes and Brandon Smith.

01:09:17.000 --> 01:09:19.000
They had been in the meeting with us.

01:09:19.000 --> 01:09:22.000
They were just doing what they wanted us to do.

01:09:22.000 --> 01:09:23.000
And they were talking.

01:09:23.000 --> 01:09:25.000
We were walking down the stairs.

01:09:25.000 --> 01:09:27.000
I was kind of right behind them.

01:09:27.000 --> 01:09:32.000
And they said, you know, he's niggas going suffer because they don't know what they're doing.

01:09:32.000 --> 01:09:34.000
They can't handle a minor like that.

01:09:34.000 --> 01:09:38.000
And I remember Cohen saying, they hurt my feeling, but it was true.

01:09:38.000 --> 01:09:47.000
He said, you know Hayes and Nathan niggas alone say, my motto is give them anything they ask you for.

01:09:47.000 --> 01:09:50.000
Bring me back and give me back to you the next day.

01:09:50.000 --> 01:09:53.000
I said, well, I see that.

01:09:53.000 --> 01:09:56.000
Well, they gone suffer for it because they could have had this money.

01:09:56.000 --> 01:09:57.000
They won't get it.

01:09:57.000 --> 01:10:00.000
And I told them she was kind of, you know, she was here.

01:10:00.000 --> 01:10:03.000
And then to us, the other she talked to us and she was printing everything.

01:10:03.000 --> 01:10:04.000
He's a man.

01:10:04.000 --> 01:10:05.000
Hayes and Brandon Smith.

01:10:05.000 --> 01:10:08.000
So I told him, I said, I said, miss Smith.

01:10:08.000 --> 01:10:11.000
I said, one thing about it, we're used to suffer.

01:10:11.000 --> 01:10:13.000
And I know some people that's not used to this.

01:10:13.000 --> 01:10:15.000
So that's who it's going to hurt.

01:10:15.000 --> 01:10:18.000
And she didn't say anything else.

01:10:18.000 --> 01:10:19.000
We kept walking.

01:10:19.000 --> 01:10:25.000
But anyway, it was rough that first year they wouldn't, every time that,

01:10:25.000 --> 01:10:29.000
we'd come in, the government would veto it.

01:10:29.000 --> 01:10:32.000
And then they would have to override them to get the money.

01:10:32.000 --> 01:10:33.000
So that's more time.

01:10:33.000 --> 01:10:39.000
And therefore, I remember at the end of those six weeks, they didn't tell us anything.

01:10:39.000 --> 01:10:42.000
When I knew anything, we knew anything at the center where I were.

01:10:42.000 --> 01:10:46.000
But they were coming in to get all the furniture and everything out.

01:10:46.000 --> 01:10:49.000
They'd give them the chairs and tables and everything.

01:10:49.000 --> 01:10:55.000
And they said there was something, miss Smith, something I don't know what it was.

01:10:55.000 --> 01:11:03.000
But anyway, we started working right away on trying to get, get refunded.

01:11:03.000 --> 01:11:07.000
I'm going to stop right here because of that.

01:11:07.000 --> 01:11:15.000
But we should know that CDGM was voted as the best head start program in the country that summer.

01:11:15.000 --> 01:11:22.000
And tell us what it was like to be working in that center about the kids, about the program for the day.

01:11:22.000 --> 01:11:27.000
It was wonderful that we had.

01:11:27.000 --> 01:11:35.000
The final money was enough so that everything you needed to operate was called.

01:11:35.000 --> 01:11:38.000
They had food like you would get at a restaurant.

01:11:38.000 --> 01:11:45.000
They had steaks, pork chops, sauces and eggs and everything for breakfast and lunch and everything.

01:11:45.000 --> 01:11:50.000
If someone came there at three o'clock, they would steal some food that you could see.

01:11:50.000 --> 01:11:54.000
Sometimes the people from Jackson will come and they will come and eat.

01:11:54.000 --> 01:12:03.000
But we had everything we had been using equipment and stuff that the farmers, different carpenter's, deals for.

01:12:03.000 --> 01:12:06.000
We got everything we needed in the chair.

01:12:06.000 --> 01:12:09.000
It was so beautiful to cheer.

01:12:09.000 --> 01:12:12.000
What about teaching?

01:12:12.000 --> 01:12:17.000
We were trying to teach them just like regular.

01:12:17.000 --> 01:12:25.000
When first we had to get them used to coming out and being away from home and for me and people.

01:12:25.000 --> 01:12:37.000
I remember the first group we had a shower in the center and some of the children would come and pick them up out of the bed and make clothes for them.

01:12:37.000 --> 01:12:41.000
We had to get in the shower with them.

01:12:41.000 --> 01:12:46.000
We could get in the shower with the children and bathe them in the shower.

01:12:46.000 --> 01:12:48.000
They had never seen a shower.

01:12:48.000 --> 01:12:51.000
Some of them never seen commos in the bathroom before.

01:12:51.000 --> 01:12:54.000
They had outside toys.

01:12:54.000 --> 01:12:57.000
We would teach the children.

01:12:57.000 --> 01:12:59.000
We started out. We would teach them.

01:12:59.000 --> 01:13:01.000
We did this even before we had money.

01:13:01.000 --> 01:13:06.000
We would teach them about letting them tell us things about that they knew.

01:13:06.000 --> 01:13:08.000
We would write it down.

01:13:08.000 --> 01:13:11.000
We would read it back to them.

01:13:11.000 --> 01:13:14.000
It would be like, thank Father Greenberg, we had a book.

01:13:14.000 --> 01:13:17.000
She wrote about some things that we did like that.

01:13:17.000 --> 01:13:24.000
We taught them how to use the taught and how to bathe themselves.

01:13:24.000 --> 01:13:29.000
We taught them how to share with other children.

01:13:29.000 --> 01:13:36.000
We taught them how to speak.

01:13:36.000 --> 01:13:42.000
They had been there for the first two weeks.

01:13:42.000 --> 01:13:45.000
It was like they didn't want to go home in the evening.

01:13:45.000 --> 01:13:49.000
They were just so proud of being there.

01:13:49.000 --> 01:13:56.000
When we had the first little graduation, we were so proud that they had learned.

01:13:56.000 --> 01:14:01.000
Some of the teachers came from the school and they couldn't believe that those children had learned.

01:14:01.000 --> 01:14:04.000
They were able to write their names.

01:14:04.000 --> 01:14:06.000
They could print their names.

01:14:06.000 --> 01:14:09.000
They could recognize every child in the class and recognize their names.

01:14:09.000 --> 01:14:12.000
We had cards for the children with their names on.

01:14:12.000 --> 01:14:13.000
We had a chair.

01:14:13.000 --> 01:14:18.000
We were practicing with them and getting everybody's chair.

01:14:18.000 --> 01:14:19.000
They had a name you called.

01:14:19.000 --> 01:14:21.000
They could go and find that chair.

01:14:21.000 --> 01:14:26.000
They could find the colors of all the chairs with different colors.

01:14:26.000 --> 01:14:29.000
The tables, some of them with different colors.

01:14:29.000 --> 01:14:33.000
That's how we taught what we had, whatever we had.

01:14:33.000 --> 01:14:37.000
We would go outside and let the children find things outside.

01:14:37.000 --> 01:14:39.000
They would count the cards.

01:14:39.000 --> 01:14:41.000
They would count the bills.

01:14:41.000 --> 01:14:44.000
They would count the trees, the flowers, and everything.

01:14:44.000 --> 01:14:46.000
That taught them so much.

01:14:46.000 --> 01:14:51.000
Some of the parents didn't know some of those things.

01:14:51.000 --> 01:14:52.000
They teach their children.

01:14:52.000 --> 01:14:54.000
That's why they didn't know.

01:14:54.000 --> 01:14:58.000
I learned a lot of that to you myself.

01:14:58.000 --> 01:15:00.000
That's how children learn.

01:15:00.000 --> 01:15:03.000
They learn whatever their environment is.

01:15:03.000 --> 01:15:07.000
You could see how the children was progressing.

01:15:07.000 --> 01:15:10.000
It was so hurt for when they said,

01:15:10.000 --> 01:15:14.000
the money was gone, we could not get fond of it.

01:15:14.000 --> 01:15:16.000
We started working on it.

01:15:16.000 --> 01:15:18.000
I just asked about that.

01:15:18.000 --> 01:15:21.000
The CDGM, although it was the best program in the country,

01:15:21.000 --> 01:15:26.000
was not refunded because Senator John (Senator John) Stennis and others believed

01:15:26.000 --> 01:15:28.000
that it was a civil rights order.

01:15:28.000 --> 01:15:29.000
That's what they say.

01:15:29.000 --> 01:15:32.000
The money coming into the state, they couldn't make it.

01:15:32.000 --> 01:15:37.000
What happened here when you found that no longer,

01:15:37.000 --> 01:15:40.000
there was temporary funding for a while,

01:15:40.000 --> 01:15:43.000
and then they cut it off completely.

01:15:43.000 --> 01:15:46.000
How did that start evolve through all this?

01:15:46.000 --> 01:15:48.000
We didn't lose count again, Mileston.

01:15:48.000 --> 01:15:51.000
We started working all over again just like the movement.

01:15:51.000 --> 01:15:55.000
We started working, getting people together and trying to,

01:15:55.000 --> 01:15:59.000
we even got a bus, my second dollar,

01:15:59.000 --> 01:16:02.000
and three other children and one of our teachers,

01:16:02.000 --> 01:16:05.000
the name Zellma, she lived in Cleveland.

01:16:05.000 --> 01:16:10.000
They went to Washington to live with our funds for Head Start.

01:16:10.000 --> 01:16:14.000
We all got together and rented a greyhound bus for the state.

01:16:14.000 --> 01:16:18.000
Everybody sent, how many children they wanted to,

01:16:18.000 --> 01:16:20.000
they went to the city for that trip.

01:16:20.000 --> 01:16:23.000
I was always stuck in the center keeping it.

01:16:23.000 --> 01:16:26.000
That was a water look.

01:16:26.000 --> 01:16:27.000
Yes, it was.

01:16:27.000 --> 01:16:30.000
You turned those kids loose on a congressman.

01:16:30.000 --> 01:16:32.000
Yes, that's what we did.

01:16:32.000 --> 01:16:38.000
After that, we worked for three months without funds again.

01:16:38.000 --> 01:16:40.000
We brought the food out.

01:16:40.000 --> 01:16:43.000
We worked just like when we had to be kept in the program going

01:16:43.000 --> 01:16:46.000
just like when we had fun.

01:16:46.000 --> 01:16:50.000
We worked until May of the next year,

01:16:50.000 --> 01:16:53.000
and finally got fun and again.

01:16:53.000 --> 01:16:55.000
Tell us about it.

01:16:56.000 --> 01:16:58.000
Well, we kept you long enough,

01:16:58.000 --> 01:17:01.000
but I want you to talk about what you've been doing

01:17:01.000 --> 01:17:05.000
in the years since the movement years.

01:17:05.000 --> 01:17:08.000
Well, I've gone to college.

01:17:08.000 --> 01:17:10.000
Where did you go to college?

01:17:10.000 --> 01:17:12.000
To (Tougaloo) the (one in) the Delta.

01:17:12.000 --> 01:17:16.000
It was such a long time ago.

01:17:16.000 --> 01:17:21.000
I had gone and got a two-year degree first,

01:17:21.000 --> 01:17:23.000
and I'm thinking, you know,

01:17:23.000 --> 01:17:26.000
before we all had to have a high school certificate

01:17:26.000 --> 01:17:28.000
to work with you, sorry.

01:17:28.000 --> 01:17:31.000
But every time they changed, we had to keep going.

01:17:31.000 --> 01:17:34.000
And finally, I got a CDA credential.

01:17:34.000 --> 01:17:37.000
And then a couple of years ago,

01:17:37.000 --> 01:17:39.000
they said we had to go back to school.

01:17:39.000 --> 01:17:41.000
So I had been going that time,

01:17:41.000 --> 01:17:47.000
but I had to, I had a chair that had to go to school first.

01:17:47.000 --> 01:17:49.000
So I had to let them go.

01:17:49.000 --> 01:17:52.000
And when they got finished, I started back.

01:17:52.000 --> 01:17:56.000
And then my health started kind of failing.

01:17:56.000 --> 01:17:58.000
I'm a diabetic, I typed through that bit.

01:17:58.000 --> 01:18:01.000
So it was a little much for me, and I stopped.

01:18:01.000 --> 01:18:03.000
But then this, I had,

01:18:03.000 --> 01:18:07.000
I only needed about three hours to graduate,

01:18:07.000 --> 01:18:10.000
but I just had kept putting it off.

01:18:10.000 --> 01:18:12.000
And finally, I went back down there,

01:18:12.000 --> 01:18:13.000
and I met Dr. McLean.

01:18:13.000 --> 01:18:15.000
And he told me,

01:18:15.000 --> 01:18:20.000
now he was in 78 when I got my two-year degree.

01:18:20.000 --> 01:18:26.000
And he was saying, he wasn't sure if the college would accept everything I had,

01:18:26.000 --> 01:18:30.000
but they had a way that they could have me to brush up on some of them.

01:18:30.000 --> 01:18:32.000
And that's what we're doing now.

01:18:32.000 --> 01:18:37.000
But I kept, I kept all,

01:18:37.000 --> 01:18:41.000
I've been working at his side for the seven years now.

01:18:41.000 --> 01:18:43.000
Wow. That is amazing.

01:18:43.000 --> 01:18:45.000
I'm still there.

01:18:45.000 --> 01:18:48.000
Thank you so much for sharing your story with us.

01:18:48.000 --> 01:18:50.000
This was inspirational.

01:18:50.000 --> 01:18:54.000
I know the people who read the transcript

01:18:54.000 --> 01:18:58.000
and watch this at the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture

01:18:58.000 --> 01:19:03.000
will be as excited as we are here to have you tell the story.

01:19:03.000 --> 01:19:06.000
Wow. That is right.

01:19:06.000 --> 01:19:09.000
You nailed it.

01:19:09.000 --> 01:19:13.000
This has been a presentation of the Library of Congress

01:19:13.000 --> 01:19:19.000
of the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.
